'''Abdullah ibn Ja'far''' ({{lang-ar|عبد الله بن جعفر}}) was a [[sahaba|companion]] and relative of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] and a nephew of [[Ali]]. [[Muhammad ibn Abu Bakr]] was his step brother. He was loyal to [[Ahl al-Bayt]] in spite of his absent in Karbala, it is attributed to his credit saying that thanks to Almight Allah, if I could not support Hussain ibn Ali in Karbala my two sons (Aun o Muhammad) did.<ref name="Badr Shahin">{{cite book|last1=Shahin|first1= Badr|title=Lady Zaynab| date=2002|publisher= Ansariyan Publications |location=Qum, Iran|page= 82|language=English|isbn=964-438-399-0}}</ref> According to [[Richard Francis Burton]] he widely recognized as the most sympathetic amongst Arabs. His grave is situated near [[Aqeel ibn Abi Talib]] and Abu Sufiyan bin al-Haris (the grandson of [[Abd al-Muttalib]]) in [[Al-Baqi|Janatual Baqi)]]<ref name=" Richard Francis Burton ">{{cite book|last1= Francis Burton |first1= Sir Richard|title= Personal Narrative of a Pilgrimage to Al-Madinah & Meccah, Volume 2| date=1893 |publisher= The Meccan Press, 3 Soho Square, London, W |location=UK|page= 44|language=English}}</ref> [[File:Grave abdullah bin Jafar(left)and Akil bin abi Talib.jpg|thumb|The Grave of Abdullah bin Jaffar-e-Tayyar in Al-Baqi]]
==Early life== He was the son of [[Ja'far ibn Abu Talib]] and [[Asma bint Umais]]. They had emigrated to [[Second migration to Abyssinia|Abyssinia]] in 616, and Abdullah and his two brothers were born there.<ref name=Saad8>Muhammad ibn Saad. ''Kitab al-Tabaqat al-Kabir'' vol. 8. Translated by Bewley, A. (1995). ''The Women of Madina''. London: Ta-Ha Publishers.</ref>{{rp|196}} Abdullah was the first of Muslims to be born in the land of Abyssinia <ref name= "Al Refai">{{cite book|last1= Dr. Ayman Odaibat |first1= Dr. Mona Borhan Ghazal (Al Refai) |title= Virtuous Women In Mythology and Holy Books (English translation from Arabic)| date= 3 March 2013 |publisher= Author House |location=Bloomington, Indiana |page= 189|language=English }}</ref> After birth of Abdullah in Abyssinia (Habesha Presently Ethiopia), king of the Kingdom of Aksum ( [[Armah|Al-Najashi]]) was blessed with a son too. He immediately asked the parents of Abdullah Ibn Jaffar about the name of their child. Upon knowing the name of Jaffar family, King of Abyssinia also chose the name “Abdullah” for his first son. It is also stated that Asma bint Umays was the nursing mother of son of Abyssinian King.<ref name= "Excerpt">{{cite book|last1= Khan |first1= Ashfaq Ahmed |title= Sakhawat Ka Darya the 5th series of books "Daur-e-Nabuwat kay bacchay (Children during Prophethood)| date= |publisher= Darus Salam (International publisher)|location=Pakistan, UK, USA & Saudi Arab |page= 12|language=Urdu }} PDF link:[https://pdfbooksfree.pk/daur-e-nabuwat-ke-bache/]</ref> The younger brother of Abdullah appears to be the first child in the Muslim history who was named Muhammad after the Prophet of Islam.<ref>{{cite web|author=A. Hamid |url=http://www.fountainmagazine.com/Issue/detail/Jafar-Ibn-Abi-Talib |title= Jafar Ibn Abi Talib |publisher=The Fountain Magazine | date= June 1995 |accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> The family returned to Arabia in 628 and settled in [[Medina]].<ref name=Saad8/>{{rp|196}}
===Muhammad's Supplication & instruction=== In addition to [[Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani|Ibn Hajar]]' reference,it is said that after 3 days of Jafar’s death Muhammad went to house of Asma and called for children of Jafar. He then said about each of them “As for Muhammad, he resemble our uncle Abi Talib. As for Abdullah, he resembles me in terms of both my appearance and character. Afterward, Muhammad took the right hand of Abdullah and said “O Allah, provide a successor for Jafar in his family, and bless Abdullah in his business, and repeated this appeal to Al-mighty thrice.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Faisal Shafeeq |first1= Dr.Ali Muhammad As-Sallaabee |title= The Noble Life of the Prophet| date= 2001 |publisher= Kalamullah.com |location=UK|pages= 1661–1662|language=English}}</ref><ref name= "Al Refai"/> Muhammad instructed the sons of Abi Talib, namely Jafar, Aqeel and Ali that they should arrange marriages of their children with their cousins.<ref>{{Citation | last = Shaikh Abbas Borhany | first = Qazi Dr. | title = Syedah Zainab, Protector of the Renaissance of Karbala | pages =5–6 | newspaper = The Weekly Mag | location = Pakistan | date = 30 June – 6 July 1994 | url = http://www.durrenajaf.com/upload/5241055e809ae.pdf | archive-url = | archive-date = 2017-12-18 }}</ref>
==Marriage and Family Life== Ali had particularly wished that his daughters should marry Ja'far's sons.<ref name=Saad8/>{{rp|299}} When Abdullah asked for [[Zaynab bint Ali|Zainab]]'s hand, Ali accepted it.<ref name="Akbar Rizvi">{{cite book|last1=Akbar Rizvi|first1= Syed Ali|title=Bibi Zainab (s.a) - Granddaughter of Prophet Muhammad (pbuh) | date=2007|publisher=Idara Tarveej-e-Uloom-e-Islamia|location=Karachi, Pakistan|pages= 30|language=English}}</ref> Abdullah and Zainab had five children. *Ali ibn Abdullah. *Awn ibn Abdullah. *Abbas ibn Abdullah. *Muhammad ibn Abdullah. *Umm Kulthum bint Abdullah.<ref name=Saad8/>{{rp|300}}
According to [[Abbas Qomi|Shaikh Muhammad Abbas Qummi]], he had 20 sons from different wives, including 5 children from Zainab Binte Ali. Daira-e-Maarif Islamia (Circle of Islamic Knowledge) of [[University of Punjab]] (pages 568-70, Vol.X) describes that Zainabi is a progeny of Abdullah’s son Ali through Zainab binte Ali<ref name="Akbar Rizvi"/>{{rp|31}}
Abdullah Bin Jaffar-e-Tayyar was one of the richest people in Madina and a famous [[philanthropist]] who was called as “Bahrul Joud” which means an ocean of charity.<ref name="Akbar Rizvi"/>{{rp|35}}
When Ali became the Caliph in 656 and moved from Medina to [[Kufa]], Zainab and Abdullah joined him.<ref>{{cite web|author= Aalulbayt Global Information Center| url=http://www.holykarbala.net/english/zainab/ |title= Al-Sayeda Zainab (p.b.u.h.), the Greatest Women Messenger of Imam al-Hussain (p.b.u.h.) Revolution |publisher=Holy Karbala Net | date= 2003{{ndash}}2007 |accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>
===His wife’s journey with Hussain Ibn Ali===
It is related that Zainab already forecast the journey (journey to [[Karbala]]) before her marriage and permission for accompanying with her brother was obtained during marriage negotiations.<ref name="Zainab">{{cite book|last1= Nisar Ahmed Zainpuri |first1= Akbar Asadi, Mehdi Raza’í |title=Namoona-e-Sabr (Zainab) translation from Persian to Urdu | date=1951|publisher= Ansarian Publications |location=Qum, Iran|page= 60|language=Persian}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1= Fatima Naqvi |first1= Dr. Umme |title= The Ultimate Sacrifice for Allah: Karbala| date=December 2011 |publisher= Nashriyat-e-Walayat-e-Elahia |location=|page= 13|language=English}}</ref> With regard to Absent of Abdullah in battle of Karbala, it is said it was due to his poor eye sighting consequently he was unable to bear the rigidities of journey and war.<ref name="Akbar Rizvi"/>{{rp|37}} Knowing Hussain’s journey to Kufa, Zainab, the wife of Abdullah ibn Jaffar begged her husband’s permission to accompany her brother.<ref>{{cite web|author= Shaikh Musa Muhammad |url= http://www.alhassanain.com/english/book/book/history_library/islamic_personalities/lady_zaynab_peace_be_upon_her/011.html |title= Lady Zaynab (Peace be Upon Her) - Ubaydullah Ibn Ziyad in Kufa |publisher=Al-Hassanain Com | date=8 August 2009 |accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref> Realizing anxiousness of her husband she stated that:
{{Cquote| You know that for 55 years my brother and I have never been separated. Now is the time of our old age and the closing period of our lives. If I leave him now, how shall I be able to face my mother, who at the time of her death had willed, “Zainab” after me you are both mother and sister for Hussain? It is obligatory for me to stay with you, but if I do not go with him at this time, I shall not be able to bear the separation. }} Abdullah then granted his permission and sent their two sons for the destined journey.<ref name="The Victory of Truth">{{cite book|last1=Bilgrami|first1= M.H|title=The Victory of Truth – The Life of Zaynab Binte Ali| date=1986 |publisher= Zahra Publications |location=Karachi, Pakistan|page= 82|language=English |isbn=088059-151-X}}</ref>
Abdullah was concurrently married to Layla bint Masud.<ref name=Saad8/>{{rp|300}} With reference to books ‘Nasab e Quraish Page-83’ and ‘Jameerath ul Nasab by Ibn Hazm page 62’ it is described that Layla Binte Masood bin Khalid was “Zoja-e-Sani (second wife)” through this marriage he had two daughters (Umme Muhammad and Umme Abhiha) and four sons (Yahya, Haroon, Suleh & Musa).<ref name="Mehmood Abbasi">{{cite book|last1=Abbasi|first1= Mehmood Ahmed|title=Khilafat-e-Muawiya O Yazid| date=1962|publisher=Maktab-e-Mehmoodia|location=Liaquatabad, Karachi, Pakistan|pages=276–77|language=Urdu}}</ref>
It is also found in books that after divorcing Zainab,<ref name=Lammens>Lammens, H. (1912). ''Fatima et les filles de Mahomet'', p. 125. Rome: Scripta Pontificii Instituti Biblici.</ref>{{better source| date=December 2017}} Abdullah married her sister, [[Umm Kulthum bint Ali]], who was the widow of his brother [[Muhammad ibn Ja'far|Muhammad]]. This marriage was childless, and Umm Kulthum predeceased Abdullah.<ref name=Saad8/>{{rp|299}} In line with [[Twelver]]’s rebuttal of divorce, [[Muhammad Al-Munajjid]] writes that Zainab died while married to him (Abdullah bin Jafar). There are many existing descendants of Zaynab and Abdullaah ibn Ja’far.<ref>{{cite book|last1= Al-Munajjid |first1= Muhammad Saalih |title= HOW HE TREATED THEM |publisher= Zad Publishing | location= Riyadh, Saudi Arabia |page= 128 |language=English |edition=2014 (First) | isbn= 978-603-01-6237-6 }}</ref>
==Career== '''Battles:'''With regard to his presence in the [[Battle of Camel]], it is indicated that at the end of Battle, while entrusting save return of mother of Believers to Medina under security of her brother Muhammad Bin Abi Bakar, Ali ordered for payment of 12,000/- Dirhams to Aisha. Abdullah thinking that amount as too little, brought out a huge sum for Aisha, the wife of the Prophet.<ref name="The History of al-Tabari"/>{{rp|127 (VOL.XVI)}} According to [[Ahmad ibn A'tham]] in battle of Siffin he was commanding the infantry in the army of Ali bin Abi Talib together with his cousin Muslim bin Aqeel, Muhammad bin Hanfia and step brother Muhammad bin Abi Bakar.<ref name="Aasam Kufi">{{cite book|last1= [[Ahmad ibn A'tham|Asam Kufi]] |first1= Ahmed bin Abu Muhammad bin Ali |title=Tareekh-e-Asam Kufi| date=2002|publisher= Ali publication |location=Janazga, Mazang, Lahore, Pakistan|page= 278|language=Urdu|ISBN=}}</ref>
'''Politics:'''He was a staunch supporter of his uncle Ali in the Civil War but later disdained from politics. He maintained a reputation for liberality and patronage in Medina, earning him the nickname “the Ocean of Generosity”.<ref name= "Mamar">{{cite book|last1=Ibn Rashid |first1=Mamar |title= The Expeditions: An Early Biography of Muhammad | date=May 2014 |publisher= New York University Press |location=NY, USA |page= 316|language=English}} online ref:[https://books.google.com.pk/books?id=t099BAAAQBAJ&dq=who+was+jafar+ibn+abi+talib&source=gbs_navlinks_s]</ref> After killing of Ali Ibn Abi Talib, Abdullah bin Jaffar together with his cousins Hassan and Hussain participated in washing the body and dressed him for burial in three robes without a Kurta (a long shirt).<ref name="Tabqat Ibn Sad (Akhbar un Nabi)" >{{cite book|last1= Ibn Sad |first1= Allama Abdullah al-Imadi |title=Tabqat Ibn Sad Vol-2 (Parts-3 & 4) |publisher= Darul Ishaat | location=Karachi [[Pakistan]]|page= 192 |language=Urdu |edition=2003}}</ref>
In addition to some spy reporting to Ali Ibn Abi Talib that '''Qays bin Sad bin Ubadah''', his governor at Egypt had given allegiance to Muawiya, he received his letter which was written in perspective of affairs emerged on account of a conspiracy caused by opponent of Ali. Ali called his sons and Abdallah bin Ja'far and consulted the matter. Upon advice of Abdullah, Ali wrote a letter ordering Qays bin Sad to seek the people to give their allegiance as the Muslims have done (after the 3rd Caliph). But, if they do not, then fight them. The governor of Egypt against this communication wrote a letter to Ali Ibn Abi Talib. Then Abdullah Bin Jaffar requested his father in law to replace Qays bin Sad bin Ubadah with Muhammad Bin Abi Bakar as governor of Egypt and pleaded that if he really has gone over to Mu`awiyah, he will refuse to give up Egypt. However, according to Tabri it was a poor advice consequent to meeting of Qays bin Sad with Ali during the period of killing of Muhammad bin Abi Bakar.<ref name="The History of al-Tabari"/>{{rp|185–189 (VOL.XVI) }}
Once a Chief of Iraqi village asked Abdullah Bin Jafar to recommend his case before Caliph Ali for accomplishment. He did so and matter of that chief was satisfied by Ali Ibn Abi Talib. As a gratification the chief sent 40,000 Darhims through some people to Abdullah, who refused the money saying that we do not sell our good deeds<ref>{{cite book|last1= Mufti Afzal Hoosen Elias |first1= Shaykh Muhammad Yusuf Kandhelvi |title= Hayat Us Sahaba - (English translation from Urdu) Volume 2 | date=March 2006 |publisher= Zem Zem, Publisher, Urdu Bazar |location= Karachi, Pakistan|page= 282|language=English}}.</ref>
==His vision for Hussain== Knowing death of his two sons in the battle of Karbala, people were offering condolences to Abdullah, one of his Mawili (Abu al-Lislas [a companion]) said that “this is what we have met and what has come upon us through Hussain Ibn Ali” on this statement he struck him with his sandal and told that I am pleased that my two sons killed with my brother and cousin. By God! If I had been present with him, I would have preferred not to leave him in order that I would be killed with him. He then seeking attention of people consoling him, said that “Praise be to God, Who has made life hard, console Hussain Ibn Ali with my own hands, my two sons consoled him.<ref name="The History of al-Tabari"/> {{rp|177}}
===Letter to Hussain=== According to [[Ibn Khaldun]] in chapter 2 volume II title “Yazid-I” from 60 to 64 AH, it is described that Abdullah sent a letter through his sons Awn & Muhammad, to Hussain, requesting that “for God sack come back”. It is my advice to you in anxiety that you would be killed and Ahle-Bayt destroyed. As a result, earth’s light will come to an end, there would be no leader for Muslims. Please do not hurry in journey, I would be reaching there after this letter.<ref>{{cite book|last1= Illabadi |first1= Hakeem Ahmed Hussain |title=Tareekh-e-Ibn Khaldun by Nafees Academy | location=Karachi [[Pakistan]]|page= 522 |language=Urdu |edition=2003}}</ref> Later he went to Amr bin Said who was Yazid's governor of Mecca and asked him to write a letter to Hussain offering him a guarantee of harmless behavior assuring him your kindness and open-handedness. Show trust to him in your letter and request him to return. This letter was replied by Hussain too.<ref name="The History of al-Tabari">{{cite book|last1=I.K.A. Howard |first1=Al-Tabari |title= The Caliphate of Yazid b. Mutawiyah|publisher= State University of New York Press | location=New York|pages=73–74 (Volume XIX) |language=English}}</ref>
