{{Infobox person |name = Afonso de Paiva |caption = Statue of Afonso de Paiva in [[Aveiro, Portugal|Aveiro]] |birth_name = |birth_date = c. 1443 |birth_place = [[Castelo Branco, Portugal|Castelo Branco]], [[Kingdom of Portugal]] |death_date = c. 1490 |death_place = [[Africa]] |nationality = [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] |occupation = [[Explorer]], [[diplomacy|diplomat]] |known_for = |signature = }} '''Afonso de Paiva''' (c. 1443 &ndash; c. 1490) was a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[diplomacy|diplomat]] and [[explorer]] of [[Ethiopia]] and the [[Barbary Coast]] together with [[Pêro da Covilhã]].<ref name="Newitt2004">{{cite book|author=Malyn Newitt|title=A History of Portuguese Overseas Expansion 1400–1668|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HDODAgAAQBAJ|date=5 November 2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-55304-4|page=50}}</ref> According to [[James Bruce]], Afonso left Pêro da Covilhã at [[Aden]], and proceeded to [[Suakin]] where he hoped to join a caravan to his destination. The further details of his life are not recorded. Bruce writes, "only that De Paiva, attempting his journey this way, lost his life, and was never more heard of."<ref>James Bruce, ''Travels to Discover the Source of the Nile'' (1805 edition), vol. 3, p. 185</ref>''
