[[File:Aistulf follis 80000860.jpg|thumb|A ''[[follis]]'' of Aistulf]]

'''Aistulf''' (died 756) was the [[Duke of Friuli]] from 744, King of [[Lombards]] from 749, and [[Duchy of Spoleto|Duke of Spoleto]] from 751.<ref name="Ulwencreutz2013">{{cite book|author=Lars Ulwencreutz|title=Ulwencreutz's The Royal Families in Europe V|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpQlBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA350|date=November 2013|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-304-58135-8|page=350–}}</ref> His father was the [[Pemmo of Friuli|Duke Pemmo]].<ref name="Hodgkin1899">{{cite book|author=Thomas Hodgkin|title=Italy and Her Invaders: Frankish invasions, 744-744|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MQQVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA164|year=1899|publisher=Clarendon Press|page=164}}</ref>

After his brother [[Ratchis]] became king, Aistulf succeeded him in Friuli. He succeeded him later as king when Ratchis abdicated to a monastery.  Aistulf continued the policy of expansion and raids against the [[papacy]] and the [[Byzantine Empire|Eastern Roman]] [[exarchate of Ravenna]]. In 751, he captured [[Ravenna]] itself and even threatened [[Rome]], claiming a [[tax per head|capitation tax]]. He also conquered the [[Istria]] region from Eastern Roman occupation in the same year.

The popes, thoroughly irritated and alarmed, and despairing of aid from the Roman Emperor, turned to the [[Carolingian]] [[mayors of the palaces|mayors of the palace]] of [[Austrasia]], the effective rulers of the [[Franks|Frankish kingdom]]. In 741, [[Pope Gregory III]] asked [[Charles Martel]] to intervene, but he was too busy elsewhere and declined. In 753, [[Pope Stephen II]] visited Charles Martel's son [[Pepin the Short]], who had been proclaimed king of the Franks in 751 with the consent of [[Pope Zachary]]. In gratitude for the papal consent to his coronation, Pepin crossed the [[Alps]], defeated Aistulf, and gave to the pope the lands which Aistulf had torn from the ''ducatus Romanus'' and the exarchate ([[Emilia-Romagna]] and the [[Pentapolis]]).

Aistulf died hunting in 756. He was succeeded by [[Desiderius]] as king of the Lombards and by [[Alboin of Spoleto|Alboin]] as duke of [[Spoleto]]. He had given Friuli to his brother-in-law [[Anselm, Duke of Friuli|Anselm]], abbot of [[Nonantula]], whose sister Gisaltruda he had married, when he succeeded to the kingship in 749.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.germantribes.org/tribes/Lombards/Lombard%20Rulers/kingsline.htm
| title       = German Tribes org Lombard Kings
